Cover.Slides and datasets to accompany coronav: Transport use change
Source: Department for Transport (DfT)
DfT provides daily updates to the Cabinet Office for use in the government’s daily media briefings on changes in:
1. road traffic in Great Britain
2. rail passenger journeys in Great Britain
3. Transport for London’s (TfL) tube and bus routes
4. bus travel in Great Britain (excluding London)
Although daily data is being reported, direct comparisons of change should not be made between weekdays and weekends/bank holidays.

For public transport there are typically different levels of service/timetable in place on weekends and bank holidays than on weekdays; and for road traffic, there is a different profile on weekend days compared to weekdays.
The data is sent as near to real time as possible.
DfT have published information on the data sources and methodology used to generate each of these headline measures:
https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-transport-data-methodology-note/covid-19-transport-data-methodology-note

Global death comparison
Source: Office for National Statistics (ONS), National Records Scotland (NRS), Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA), Public Health England, John Hopkins University
Country data is aligned by stage of the outbreak. Day 0 equals the first day 50 or more deaths were reported.
Daily reporting of UK deaths is for hospitals only and may lag by up to several days.
ONS, NRS and NISRA reporting of UK deaths for all settings is based on information from death certificates, and therefore lags daily hospital data.
International reporting procedures and lags are unclear, so may not be comparing like-for-like.
